HOL-12: Conditional Rendering (Part 1)

Conditional rendering in React

Refers to displaying different UI based on certain conditions, like login status
Can be done using if statements, ternary operators, or logical && operators
Lets one component render completely different output depending on props or state
Central to building interactive apps that change based on user actions
Used in this lab to switch between Guest and User views

Element variables

A variable that stores a piece of JSX, decided by some condition
Makes render logic cleaner by separating the decision from the actual JSX output
The variable is later inserted into the JSX using { }
Common pattern: use if/else to assign JSX to a variable, then render that variable
Was used in this lab to decide between showing a Login or Logout button

Preventing components from rendering

A component can be prevented from rendering by returning null from its render logic
Useful when a component should conditionally not appear at all
Different from just hiding with CSS; the component doesn't render into the DOM at all
Commonly combined with conditions based on props or state
Ensures the DOM only contains elements that are actually meant to be shown

Implementing conditional rendering in React applications

The Greeting component checked props.isLoggedIn to decide which child component to show
If true, it rendered <UserGreeting />; otherwise, <GuestGreeting />
The parent App component tracked isLoggedIn in state and passed it down as a prop
Clicking Login/Logout updated state, which triggered a re-render with different output
Demonstrates how state changes drive what conditional UI gets displayed
